&lt;p&gt;Every government agency in the United States, from Homeland Security to Departments of Motor Vehicles, has the authority to make its own rules for sex classification. Many transgender people find themselves in the bizarre situation of having different sex classifications on different documents. Whether you can change your legal sex to &amp;ldquo;F&amp;rdquo; or &amp;ldquo;M&amp;rdquo; (or more recently &amp;ldquo;X&amp;rdquo;) depends on what state you live in, what jurisdiction you were born in, and what government agency you&amp;rsquo;re dealing with. In this panel discussion centered on noted transgender advocate and scholar &lt;strong&gt;Paisley Currah&amp;#39;s new book, &lt;em&gt;Sex Is as Sex Does&lt;/em&gt;,&lt;/strong&gt; Currah will be joined by Professor Katherine Franke and Che Gossett to explore this deeply flawed system, and discuss why it fails transgender and non-binary people.&lt;/p&gt;
