Executive Vice President for Columbia Global; University Professor; Dr. Mathilde Krim-amfAR Professor of Global Health (in Epidemiology); Director of ICAP; Director of Columbia World Projects&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;After a military regime interrupted Chile&amp;rsquo;s long democratic tradition, its return brought a period of steady economic growth. Despite political and economic reforms, high social inequality persisted and dissatisfaction with the political system erupted into massive protests in 2019. This triggered a process of constitutional reform and increased fragmentation of the political system. In 2021, President Boric, a representative and former student leader, was elected as Chile&amp;rsquo;s youngest president on the platform of addressing this crisis of representation.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;This discussion will explore the transformation of the country&amp;rsquo;s political climate through greater government and state institutional participation of women, youth, and indigenous peoples&amp;mdash;among other politically underrepresented groups&amp;mdash;and the implication of a constitutional process that seeks to expand social rights and face new challenges.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
